On the third day of my internship, I implemented the Canny edge detection algorithm using the 
OpenCV library. The purpose of this task was to apply the theoretical knowledge gained on the 
previous day and observe the algorithm's performance in practice. Python was used as the 
programming language, and a sample image was selected for the experiments.

First, the original image was loaded into the program. To reduce image noise, Bilateral Filter, Median 
Blur, and Gaussian Blur techniques were applied, and their outputs were compared. The filtered 
images are presented in Figure 1, Figure 2, and Figure 3 in Appendix 1.

Next, the image was converted into grayscale, which is a required preprocessing step for the Canny 
algorithm. The grayscale image is shown in Figure 4 in Appendix 1.

Finally, the Canny edge detection function provided by OpenCV was applied to the image. The 
resulting output successfully highlighted the main edges of the object while suppressing most
unnecessary background details. The final edge detection result is presented in Figure 5 in Appendix 1.

By the end of the day, I gained practical experience in implementing the Canny edge detection 
algorithm using OpenCV and developed a better understanding of the image processing steps that 
will be used in the virtual piano project.
